<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHLAND CONGESTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Prof. Gordon Fielding is only partly right ("Focus on Congestion, Not More 
Freeways," Op-Ed Page, Feb. 6). The focus should be on reducing the use of 
automobiles and trucks, as he says. 
</P>
<P>
But he is wrong to ignore the essential cause of our dilemma, the gross subsidy 
our society presently provides the motorist and particularly, the trucking 
industry. It would require an increase of 50 cents per gallon, alone, to 
reimburse the property taxpayers for local government services that drivers do 
not now pay for. 
</P>
<P>
He is also right to call attention to the huge financial cost needed to pay for 
" . . . Building our way out. . . ." He says it would cost 18 cents per gallon, 
but he doesn't say for how many years. Another, possibly more explicit, figure 
is $100 billion, or $25,000 per family, for all the families in the Los Angeles 
metropolitan area. 
</P>
<P>
Finally, his conclusion is (almost) exactly right. We must place the cost of 
transportation on the shoulders of the user, not on the community as a whole. 
He should also have instructed us that the problem affects not only traffic 
congestion; it also directly affects, grossly and adversely, our environment 
and our economy. 
</P>
<P>
STANLEY HART 
</P>
<P>
Altadena 
</P>
</TEXT>
