<HEADLINE>
<P>
DREXEL 'JUNK BOND' UNIT REPORTEDLY TO STAY IN SOUTHLAND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOT J. PALTROW, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Securities and Exchange Commission will permit Drexel Burnham Lambert's 
highly profitable "junk bond" department to remain in Beverly Hills under terms 
of a settlement likely to be made public soon, sources close to the 
negotiations said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
In talks on settling pending SEC charges of fraud, insider trading and stock 
market manipulation, the agency had demanded that Drexel move the high-yield 
junk bond operation back to the firm's headquarters in New York, where SEC 
officials felt it could be more closely supervised. 
</P>
<P>
But Drexel strongly resisted, claiming that closure of the office would be 
catastrophic to the firm's business. Officials said they feared an exodus of 
key employees who were reluctant to move. The junk bond department, headed by 
Michael Milken, has been the direct or indirect source of most of Drexel's 
profits. Its activities also have been the source of nearly all of the firm's 
legal problems with federal regulators and the U.S. Attorney's Office in 
Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
The threat of being forced to close the Beverly Hills office prompted Drexel in 
January to mount a lobbying campaign with Los Angeles city officials and 
congressmen from California. Both of California's senators and seven 
representatives wrote to SEC Chairman David S. Ruder asking that Drexel be 
permitted to keep the office open. 
</P>
<P>
Terms of the settlement, however, were worked out with the SEC's enforcement 
staff. Ruder and the other commissioners are believed not to have officially 
considered it yet, and it isn't known if they played any role in shaping it. 
The commissioners must formally approve the settlement before it becomes 
official. 
</P>
<P>
The Beverly Hills office was founded by Milken in 1978. He had almost 
single-handedly developed Drexel's hugely profitable junk bond business in New 
York and then won approval to move the department to his native Los Angeles. 
The junk bond operation has been a major force in financing hostile corporate 
raids and leveraged buyouts. Although the department nominally was under 
control from New York, Milken in actuality was allowed much independence. 
</P>
<P>
The accord would end the SEC's lawsuit, which has been pending against Drexel 
since September. It also would clear the way for Drexel to carry out its 
announced agreement with federal prosecutors in New York to plead guilty to six 
criminal counts and pay $650 million in penalties. Under that agreement, Drexel 
is also supposed to fire Milken and deprive him of his 1988 bonus. But that 
provision is being challenged in court by Milken's lawyers. Milken, who denies 
any wrongdoing, is still expected to be indicted on a variety of securities 
fraud and racketeering charges. 
</P>
<P>
Although the core of the junk bond operation will remain in Beverly Hills, the 
agreement will, as expected, require Drexel to move some peripheral operations 
back to New York, sources said. These include trading in convertible securities 
and the limited trading in stocks carried out by the high-yield department. 
</P>
<P>
Although the junk bond operation will remain where it is, the Beverly Hills 
office will be subject to much closer scrutiny under provisions of the 
tentative settlement, the sources said. The firm will be required to name at 
least two outside directors to its 22-member board, and it will pay for the 
services of a Philadelphia-based law firm, Morgan, Lewis &amp; Bockius, 
selected by the SEC, to closely review Drexel's compliance with securities 
laws. 
</P>
<P>
It is understood that one reason the firm was selected is that it has offices 
in Los Angeles as well as in New York. A member of the law firm's management 
committee noted that the SEC commissioners hadn't taken final action on the 
settlement yet and so declined to comment on reports that his firm had been 
selected to monitor Drexel's compliance. 
</P>
<P>
The Morgan Lewis firm has been retained before to conduct this type of 
monitoring for the SEC. It was hired in 1987 to review procedures at Los 
Angeles-based Jefferies &amp; Co., a brokerage firm, after its founder and 
chief executive, Boyd L. Jefferies, pleaded guilty to securities fraud charges. 
The law firm found no major problems at Jefferies. But some congressmen and 
others at the time criticized the selection of Morgan Lewis because the firm 
had been Jefferies &amp; Co.'s outside counsel while Boyd Jefferies carried out 
his illegal activities. 
</P>
<P>
Morgan Lewis, however, doesn't represent Drexel. And a source said the SEC is 
likely to require a much more extensive review of Drexel than it required of 
Jefferies &amp; Co. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
JUNK BONDS; DREXEL BURNHAM LAMBERT INC; SECURITIES FRAUD; INSIDER INFORMATION; 
MILKEN, MICHAEL; RELOCATION OF BUSINESS; SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION; 
SETTLEMENTS; GOVERNMENT REGULATION 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA022289-0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 21932 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 22, 1989, Wednesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part 4; Page 1; Column 5; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
840 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
U.S. EXPECTS TO PAY $30 BILLION TO CLOSE S&amp;LS; 
</P>
<P>
BUSH SEEKS $44 BILLION MORE FOR MERGERS; SKEPTICS CALL PLAN TOO OPTIMISTIC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROBERT A. ROSENBLATT, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Bush Administration, unveiling financial details of its savings and loan 
rescue plan, said Tuesday that it expects to spend $30 billion to shut crippled 
S&amp;Ls and pay off depositors over the next 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
The plan also calls for additional outlays of $44 billion on "assisted" 
mergers, with the government offering substantial financial incentives and 
guarantees to persuade outside investors to buy ailing institutions. 
</P>
<P>
However, both figures may be too low, because they don't include enough funds 
to dispose of S&amp;Ls that are now solvent but ultimately will become too weak 
to survive, experts warned. 
</P>
<P>
"These numbers are understated -- conservatively you can add another $30 billon 
or more to the total," warned Robert Litan of the Brookings Institution. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Bond Issue Required 
</P>
<P>
The Administration plan, which will be formally presented to Congress today by 
Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady, depends on a bond issue and premiums 
collected from savings institutions for the financial rescue. 
</P>
<P>
The total price has been estimated at $126 billion over 10 years. Besides the 
outlays to shut insolvent S&amp;Ls and help finance new mergers, the package 
includes $52 billion to cover future costs of sales and mergers that have 
already been consummated. 
</P>
<P>
Specific details of the plan, including the amount to be spent on future 
S&amp;L closures, were issued Tuesday by the Office of Management and Budget. 
</P>
<P>
The Administration plan is directed at 350 insolvent institutions in which 
liabilities exceed assets. 
</P>
<P>
Several hundred more may be solvent now, but are weak and unlikely to meet the 
tougher capital standards called for by the Bush program. "There are a lot more 
basket cases, and that's where I'm questioning whether they have enough money," 
Litan said. 
</P>
<P>
Rising interest rates will drive up the cost of doing business for these weak 
institutions because they will be compelled to pay higher rates to attract 
deposits. 
</P>
<P>
Although outlays would extend over a decade, the centerpiece of the Bush plan 
is a special bond issue to provide federal regulators with funds quickly to 
shut down insolvent institutions. 
</P>
<P>
If Congress approves the Bush program, $50 billion in bonds would be sold over 
the next three years to provide immediate cash. The balance of the $126 billion 
would come from premiums paid by financial institutions and from approximately 
$40 billion in taxpayer funds. 
</P>
<P>
However, some experts say the short-range need is greater than $50 billion. 
</P>
<P>
"That is clearly not enough," said Bert Ely, a financial consultant. "They 
should have gone for $65 billion. " 
</P>
<P>
The money "doesn't come fast enough," Ely said. More funds will be needed to 
close weak institutions that engage in costly rate wars, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Ailing S&amp;Ls commonly offer unusually high rates of interest to attract 
deposits, a policy that drives up costs for the rest of the industry, hurting 
the healthy S&amp;Ls by forcing them to pay extraordinary rates to stay 
competitive. 
</P>
<P>
The federal savings and loan insurance fund, which guarantees deposits up to 
$100,000, is currently insolvent. Regulators have been forced to permit many 
crippled S&amp;Ls to stay in business because there is not enough money to shut 
them down. 
</P>
<P>
Under the Bush plan, regulation of S&amp;Ls is shifting to the Federal Deposit 
Insurance Corp., which oversees the safety of bank deposits up to $100,000. The 
FDIC already is moving to seize control of more than 200 insolvent institutions 
while waiting for Congress to act on the Bush plan. The former S&amp;L 
regulator, the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp., will provide personnel 
to work under FDIC leadership. 
</P>
<P>
This extraordinary concentration of regulatory power was sharply questioned 
Tuesday by Rep. Frank Annunzio (D-Ill.), chairman of the subcommittee that will 
write the S&amp;L rescue legislation. 
</P>
<P>
Annunzio said the FDIC's "current level of supervision over the banks that it 
insures is inadequate." In Texas, for example, the FDIC is responsible for 617 
banks, but has not examined 73 of those banks since 1985, he said in a 
statement on the House floor. 
</P>
<P>
"The FDIC already insures $1.68 trillion in 8,400 banks, and I am concerned 
that it is too overextended to take on new work," said Annunzio, who is 
chairman of the financial institutions subcommittee of the House Banking 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
"Can a federal banking agency that in the past two years has not conducted . . 
. examinations of hundreds of banks under its supervision, " he asked, "be 
trusted with additional supervisory authority over thousands" of S&amp;Ls? 
</P>
<P>
Annunzio's subcommittee will conduct a quick investigation of FDIC regulation 
of banks. The subcommittee "needs to determine whether the FDIC can handle its 
own work, let alone other agencies' work," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Banking Committee Chairman Henry B. Gonzalez (D-Tex.) said "auditing 
firms must share substantial blame for the S&amp;L crisis." 
</P>
<P>
The independent accounting firms failed badly in neglecting to identify bad 
loans that were uncollectible, Frederick D. Wolf, assistant comptroller 
general, told the committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
